		<header>
			
			<h1>Simplifying EU fisheries rules: less work for more efficiency?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> In his first speech to the Advisory Committee on Fisheries and Aquaculture (ACFA) on December 10th 2004, the EU Fisheries Commissioner, Joe Borg, highlighted the EC's future priorities for fisheries. He reiterated his support for on-going processes, like the creation of the European Fisheries Control Agency or the support to the fisheries partnership approach to the EU's bilateral fisheries agreements and protocols, highlighting, in particular, the EU's action against illegal fishing activities. Concluding his list of programmed activities, Mr Borg referred to the launching of a number of topical debates on such issues as the need to simplify the EU's fisheries rules.</p><p> A week later, on December 15th, the Commission published a communication on 'Perspectives for simplifying and improving the regulatory environment of the Common Fisheries Policy'. The communication highlights the fact that EU member state administrations have voiced concern over the reporting requirements to be submitted to DG Fish and the practical use of such data. It says that 'the most sensitive issue for fishermen is the requirement to submit data, in particular via the logbook'.</p><p> The communication also acknowledges the specific issues arising from EU distant-water fishing activities (what is referred to as 'external resources'), and suggests that, for simplification, it would be important to 'define a medium-term strategy according to the type of agreement, region or type of fishery to ensure consistency in Community action aimed at achieving a sustainable fisheries policy while at the same time protecting Community interests'. It also emphasise that 'regarding bilateral relations (partnership agreements), action by the European Community, fishermen and member states (including action under other EU policies) could be improved by gradually building up standard legislative frameworks, whilst remaining open to the specific features and issues faced by the fisheries concerned, as well as by improving negotiation and follow-up procedures'.</p><p> The concrete proposals for simplification include the following:</p>
<ul>

<li>adapting logbooks and other documents to address only the specific needs of fishery management, including enforcement; </li>

<li>data flows to fishermen must also be improved, for example by promoting scientists' use of their data. </li>

</ul>
<p> The communication concludes by saying that 'it is also important to ensure that simplification does not lead to weaker management or provide an excuse for opposing any new measures that may be needed to progress policy or to address new situations'.</p><p>
 The Commission is working on a list of proposed areas for action intended to guide the discussions and target tangible initiatives. The communication specifies that 'consultation procedures needed to draw up a final action plan could therefore be held in the beginning of 2005 with the aim of presenting the plan as soon as possible in the same year'.<br /> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/discours/speech53_en.htm" target="_self">Speech by Joe Borg to the Advisory Committee on Fisheries and Aquaculture</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/eur-lex/lex/LexUriServ/site/en/com/2004/com2004_0820en01.pdf" target="_self">EC: 'Perspectives for simplifying and improving the regulatory environme...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.seaaroundus.org/newsletter/Issue12.pdf" target="_self">Newsletter 'Sea Around us', report of a symposium on fisheries in west A...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> A major stumbling block in ACP-EU fisheries relations has always been the difficulty for the ACP to know the quantities and value of EU catches in their waters, as well as the zones where these catches have been made. This is important for ACP countries, both in terms of resource management and, in the case of the signing of a bilateral fisheries deal, for the setting up of a financial compensation that reflects the amount and value of catches made.</p><p> It is important that, in the consultation procedure, ACP countries are consulted on 'specific issues arising from EU distant-water fishing activities', identified in the Commission's communication. In particular, ACP informational needs should be taken into account for the building up of standard legislative frameworks, that will specify reporting requirements for EU fleets active in ACP waters.</p><p> Specific ACP needs for managing EU activities in their waters should be addressed in EU operators' reports: quantities of catches (for both targeted species and by-catch); level of catches of juveniles; and location of the catching, should all be detailed. Emphasis should be put on using new communication technologies, so that data are available to the ACP relevant administrations in time for efficient monitoring control and surveillance. These data should also be used in EU-ACP joint scientific committees set up through bilateral fisheries partnership to adapt the level of financial compensation according to the level and value of catches as well as the administrative costs of the ACP for the management of EU fleet activities in their waters.</p><p> Given Mr Borg's commitment to support EU efforts against IUU fishing in FPAs, ACP countries should bring these matters before him as soon as possible, so that their views are taken into account in the consultative process that will be launched early in 2005.</p>
		</div>
		
